Davis said she and her former husband, Jeff, wound up expecting another child in 1996 after they decided to stop taking birth-control measures. During her second trimester, Davis said she took a blood test that could determine chromosomal or neural defects, which doctors first told her didn't warrant concern. 

After a later exam revealed the brain defect, Davis said she sought opinions from multiple doctors, who told her the baby would be deaf, blind and in a permanent vegetative state if she survived delivery.

'I could feel her little body tremble violently, as if someone were applying an electric shock to her, and I knew then what I needed to do,' Davis writes. 

'She was suffering.'

She goes on to say that an 'indescribable blackness followed' the pregnancy, and that the loss left her forever changed.

